WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:14.400
Good day, everyone. I'm Norman Wildberger.&nbsp;
In today's video, I want to do something a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:14.400 --> 00:00:20.400
little bit different. I want to go back to a paper&nbsp;
that I wrote fifteen years ago called Real Fish,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:27.060
Real Numbers, Real Jobs, where I tried to&nbsp;
start convincing my fellow mathematicians&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:27.060 --> 00:00:35.880
that there was something unsatisfactory about our&nbsp;
approach to real numbers. This article appeared in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:35.880 --> 00:00:43.770
The Mathematical Intelligencer, which is a very&nbsp;
prominent expository journal that covers a wide&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.770 --> 00:00:54.270
range of mathematics for a very broad audience.&nbsp;
The actual issue was Volume 21, Number 2, in 1999.

00:00:55.620 --> 00:01:00.600
The paper is not that long, and I'm going to&nbsp;
inflict it upon you—I'm going to read it to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:06.360
you today. I hope you'll enjoy it because it's&nbsp;
written in a somewhat tongue-in-cheek fashion,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:11.520
a little bit more lighthearted perhaps&nbsp;
than my current approach to real numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:11.520 --> 00:01:18.900
which is a little bit more forceful&nbsp;
and take-no-prisoners. And maybe we'll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:18.900 --> 00:01:21.960
talk about that after I read the paper to you.

00:01:23.790 --> 00:01:31.020
Real Fish, Real Numbers, Real Jobs
There are good times ahead for biologists.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:31.020 --> 00:01:35.190
The electronics revolution will plateau in&nbsp;
the early decades of the new millennium,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:35.190 --> 00:01:42.540
and quantum computing, gene manipulation, and pet&nbsp;
cloning will kick in. We'll see bumper crops of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.540 --> 00:01:48.030
biology graduates pouring into expanded university&nbsp;
departments, research institutes, and biotech&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:48.030 --> 00:01:54.480
companies. Some decades later, however, with&nbsp;
hemoglobin-monitoring wristwatches and desktop&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.480 --> 00:01:58.980
chicken mutators as plentiful and as much of a&nbsp;
nuisance as mobile phones and laptops are now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:58.980 --> 00:02:05.250
the spotlight of public attention and funds&nbsp;
will inevitably shift to consumer applications.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:05.250 --> 00:02:10.980
Where will that leave the ranks of theoretical&nbsp;
research biologists amassed by universities?

00:02:10.980 --> 00:02:17.520
My advice is to think now about saving the job&nbsp;
prospects of future generations of academics by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:17.520 --> 00:02:24.270
reconsidering and expanding the entire subject.&nbsp;
That's where I humbly suggest toaster fish come&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:24.270 --> 00:02:31.020
in, and where mathematicians can provide some&nbsp;
friendly help. A toaster fish is, of course,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.020 --> 00:02:37.050
a creature with the head of a toaster—the&nbsp;
pop-up kind—and the body of a fish. Thus,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:37.050 --> 00:02:44.100
Figure 1 shows a typical toaster fish. And here&nbsp;
is Figure 1. I hope you can see that down there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:44.100 --> 00:02:48.900
an artist's representation of a toaster fish.

00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:53.430
Toaster fish come in at least two different&nbsp;
varieties: the North American kind,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:53.430 --> 00:03:00.750
which operates on 120 volts, and the European&nbsp;
kind, which uses 220 volts. Already, I hear a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:00.750 --> 00:03:08.160
lot of you asking the obvious question: Can North&nbsp;
American and European toaster fish mate? This is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:08.160 --> 00:03:13.740
typical of the important new research problems&nbsp;
in the brave new world of biology I'm proposing.

00:03:13.740 --> 00:03:20.730
Biology needs to embrace the study of life in all&nbsp;
its possibilities. There is no need to restrict&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.730 --> 00:03:25.770
attention to those creatures actually living or&nbsp;
having lived or with the potential of living on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:25.770 --> 00:03:31.740
planet Earth and its immediate environs. These&nbsp;
creatures are but a happy cross-section of all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:31.740 --> 00:03:38.280
possible life forms. By widening our consideration&nbsp;
to arbitrary creatures, we can formulate new&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:38.280 --> 00:03:44.970
theories, create intellectual challenges, unleash&nbsp;
our wildest imagination, and, best of all,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.970 --> 00:03:56.100
create jobs. Let's call this emerging field "Life&nbsp;
Theory." Toaster fish, baby universes, and slimy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.100 --> 00:04:01.650
galactic super-octopi will all be embraced&nbsp;
by this farsighted new intellectual endeavor.

00:04:01.650 --> 00:04:08.250
But it won't be easy. There'll be colleagues who&nbsp;
ridicule life theory—those who call it a theory&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:08.250 --> 00:04:14.880
about nothing or quasi-religious speculation&nbsp;
on things that don't exist. Already, one of my&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:21.750
friends protests that Figure 1 amounts to little&nbsp;
more than a poetic idea since I have not specified&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.750 --> 00:04:29.350
the internal workings of the toaster fish&nbsp;
depicted. Fortunately, mathematicians have already&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:29.350 --> 00:04:35.140
encountered and triumphed over similar obstacles&nbsp;
in their historic struggle to place real numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:35.140 --> 00:04:42.160
squarely at the center of all modern mathematical&nbsp;
discourse. The modern biologist can gain from a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:47.380
careful study of this important achievement, which&nbsp;
we turn to now with an eye to the main principles.

00:04:50.650 --> 00:04:54.670
A Short History of Numbers and&nbsp;
the Importance of Terminology&nbsp;

00:04:54.670 --> 00:05:02.200
The Neanderthals gave us one, two, and&nbsp;
three. The ancients added on four, five,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:02.200 --> 00:05:07.750
six, and so on, discovered zero and negative&nbsp;
numbers, and employed rationals like 22/3.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.350 --> 00:05:13.900
They discovered that other useful&nbsp;
quantities like √2 and π were not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:13.900 --> 00:05:18.940
of this form and could only be specified&nbsp;
by algorithms, which subsequently allowed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:18.940 --> 00:05:31.720
writing them in binary expansions like&nbsp;
√2 = 1.0110101... and π = 11.0010010....

00:05:34.810 --> 00:05:42.520
The Europeans added some more useful numbers:&nbsp;
complex numbers like 5 + 2i and infinitesimals&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:51.010
like 1 + 3dx. It wasn't clear exactly what these&nbsp;
numbers were, but their use in the calculus was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:51.010 --> 00:05:56.740
undisputed, so they remained—until the 19th&nbsp;
century, that is, when new standards of rigor&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:56.740 --> 00:06:04.150
revealed that an infinitely small quantity was&nbsp;
only a grammatical construction bereft of any&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:04.150 --> 00:06:11.200
real mathematical meaning. So infinitesimals were&nbsp;
abandoned, but complex numbers were justified, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:17.800
constructible irrationals abounded. So we still&nbsp;
had numbers galore for every conceivable problem.

00:06:17.800 --> 00:06:25.540
Then came the greatest, the boldest leap of&nbsp;
all: we introduced numbers so abstract that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.540 --> 00:06:33.250
they couldn't possibly be needed for any concrete&nbsp;
problem. How? We considered binary expansions that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:33.250 --> 00:06:39.840
couldn't be constructed by definition.&nbsp;
Although this may sound contradictory,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:39.840 --> 00:06:46.650
it is not. Just consider a slimy galactic&nbsp;
super-octopus with an infinitely large brain,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:46.650 --> 00:06:51.150
an infinite number of arms, and&nbsp;
an inclination to wave them all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:51.150 --> 00:06:56.070
simultaneously and independently either&nbsp;
up or down. Looking at the configuration&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.070 --> 00:07:01.080
of arms at some random time gives a&nbsp;
generally unconstructible sequence.

00:07:01.080 --> 00:07:05.880
As an aside, I mention that such a&nbsp;
creature would be a useful friend,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:05.880 --> 00:07:12.210
being able to solve the Goldbach conjecture or&nbsp;
the Riemann hypothesis simply by computation—and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:12.210 --> 00:07:20.550
in an infinitesimally small amount of time to&nbsp;
boot! More mundanely, an uncomputable binary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:20.550 --> 00:07:27.450
expansion is simply a binary expansion that is&nbsp;
not computable. It does seem curious that such&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:27.450 --> 00:07:32.400
a simple idea eluded all the great thinkers&nbsp;
until the latter half of the 19th century.

00:07:32.400 --> 00:07:37.800
To envision such a number, we proceed&nbsp;
as follows: randomly write down a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:37.800 --> 00:07:43.290
string of zeros and ones—a dozen usually&nbsp;
suffices, but if the audience is skeptical,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:43.290 --> 00:07:56.850
I like to include more—and then add three&nbsp;
dots. Thus, α = 1.0110101111001... shows a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:56.850 --> 00:08:02.520
typical unconstructible number. These new&nbsp;
objects, when added onto the collection&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:02.520 --> 00:08:08.280
of rationals and constructible irrationals, gave&nbsp;
us a whole new domain of mathematical discourse.

00:08:08.280 --> 00:08:14.220
Now, a key point: What did we&nbsp;
call this new number system,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:14.220 --> 00:08:20.340
consisting largely of numerical creations of&nbsp;
our imagination? Did we call them arbitrary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:20.340 --> 00:08:27.960
numbers or way-out numbers? No. In a flash of&nbsp;
brilliance any PR person would be proud of,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:27.960 --> 00:08:36.450
we called them real numbers and designated them by&nbsp;
the solid-looking ℝ. This inspired terminology is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:36.450 --> 00:08:43.140
worth emulating. I suggest you call the new area&nbsp;
of modern biology concerned with toaster fish,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:51.040
refrigerator fish, and so on the field&nbsp;
of "Real Fish." Those real fish actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:51.040 --> 00:08:56.650
found in the solar system will then have a&nbsp;
special designation, subtly reinforcing the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:56.650 --> 00:09:01.390
idea that it is unnatural to consider them&nbsp;
separately—let's say "Observable Real Fish."

00:09:01.390 --> 00:09:08.830
How much more of a bother it is to consider&nbsp;
the latter! Let α be an observable real fish.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:08.830 --> 00:09:15.070
You begin your lecture—where is it from? Is it&nbsp;
green? What does it eat? Someone immediately&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:15.070 --> 00:09:22.210
asks. Therefore, preferable: Let α be a real&nbsp;
fish. This protects you from such unnecessary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.210 --> 00:09:28.660
questions, which you can't answer anyway.&nbsp;
In mathematics, restriction to computable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:28.660 --> 00:09:33.940
real numbers is a decided nuisance. First,&nbsp;
one must worry about what computable means:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:33.940 --> 00:09:40.480
which machine, which language? About&nbsp;
whether or not programs halt? Simple&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:40.480 --> 00:09:45.100
operations like adding or multiplying two&nbsp;
numbers give us headaches. Real numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:45.100 --> 00:09:49.960
free us from these hassles, which we prefer&nbsp;
to leave to the computer scientists anyway.

00:09:52.810 --> 00:09:57.160
Training the Young
How do we get future generations&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:57.160 --> 00:10:03.040
to take the validity of real numbers for granted?&nbsp;
We indoctrinate them early in their careers when&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:03.040 --> 00:10:08.200
they are eager but impressionable undergraduates.&nbsp;
Here's how we do it: First, we soften them up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:08.200 --> 00:10:14.380
with a "constructing the real numbers" blurb in&nbsp;
their first calculus course. Needless to say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:14.380 --> 00:10:19.990
we don't really construct real numbers, as they&nbsp;
are by definition unconstructible, but the phrase&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:19.990 --> 00:10:26.980
sticks in their minds long after the details are&nbsp;
forgotten. Sometime later, we expose them to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:26.980 --> 00:10:32.050
definition of a one-to-one correspondence,&nbsp;
Cantor's wonderful proof that there is no&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:32.050 --> 00:10:38.860
list of all binary sequences, and voila! There's&nbsp;
a bit of hand-waving about what a set actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:38.860 --> 00:10:45.730
is, and a vast and glittering new universe of&nbsp;
ordinals, cardinals, hierarchies of infinities,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:45.730 --> 00:10:53.320
and continuum hypotheses opens up before their&nbsp;
eyes. The confusion and apprehension of millennia&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:53.320 --> 00:11:00.850
cast aside, our students are soon fearlessly&nbsp;
manipulating arbitrary unions of arbitrarily&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:00.850 --> 00:11:09.460
many powers of uncountable ordinals. It's a heady&nbsp;
experience, this first grasping hold of infinity.

00:11:09.460 --> 00:11:15.400
But be warned: There will be some students who&nbsp;
won't buy this. After all, young people are a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:15.400 --> 00:11:20.620
tad critical at this age. We explain to them that&nbsp;
if they want to get into foundational questions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:20.620 --> 00:11:25.180
then they had better first master the&nbsp;
predicate calculus of first-order logic.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:25.180 --> 00:11:30.370
Having barely mastered the ordinary calculus,&nbsp;
they seem to find this a convincing argument.

00:11:30.370 --> 00:11:37.570
A further point: We don't start with younger&nbsp;
students, since they get too easily confused.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:37.570 --> 00:11:44.830
They want to know specifics like, how does&nbsp;
one add or multiply real numbers? In fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:44.830 --> 00:11:49.480
one can't add or multiply real numbers. But of&nbsp;
course, this shouldn't and doesn't prevent us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:49.480 --> 00:11:56.860
from using these operations on a daily basis.&nbsp;
Immature learners are likely to get stuck by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:56.860 --> 00:12:02.950
these subtleties. The snag is the following:&nbsp;
Suppose we want to add the unconstructible real&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:02.950 --> 00:12:21.850
numbers 1.01010101001... and 1.1000100111001....&nbsp;
Clearly, the first digits of the sum are 10.11,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:21.850 --> 00:12:28.690
but the next digit requires more information.&nbsp;
How much more information? Possibly just one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:28.690 --> 00:12:34.450
more digit, possibly a trillion more digits,&nbsp;
and here's the rub—possibly infinitely many&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:34.450 --> 00:12:40.600
more digits. The complementary pattern of zeros&nbsp;
and ones might continue to infinity, but if so,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:40.600 --> 00:12:47.230
we'll never know it. This prevents us from ever&nbsp;
specifying a procedure to add real numbers.

00:12:47.230 --> 00:12:52.390
One might hope that trying some different&nbsp;
definition of the reals, using continued&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:52.390 --> 00:12:58.180
fractions or Dedekind cuts or Cauchy sequences of&nbsp;
rationals, might solve the problem—but it doesn't.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:58.180 --> 00:13:05.080
It just transforms it into an equivalent one. But&nbsp;
here's where religion—or modern biology—comes to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:05.080 --> 00:13:10.870
our aid. It may be impossible for us to know&nbsp;
whether a given complementary pattern of zeros&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:10.870 --> 00:13:17.680
and ones continues indefinitely, but it is clearly&nbsp;
not impossible for God or a slimy intergalactic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:17.680 --> 00:13:24.220
super-octopus to know. So we are blessedly free to&nbsp;
go on talking about adding arbitrary real numbers.

00:13:27.250 --> 00:13:32.290
Convincing the Professorial
This is a question primarily of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:32.290 --> 00:13:38.800
critical mass. Once enough of the academy accepts&nbsp;
and profits by the new bounds of the discipline,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:38.800 --> 00:13:43.960
a critical momentum will prevent opponents&nbsp;
from stemming the tide. First of all,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:43.960 --> 00:13:50.050
a leading luminary must be taken on board. In our&nbsp;
case, that was David Hilbert, whose oft-quoted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:50.050 --> 00:13:55.090
"No one shall expel us from the paradise that&nbsp;
Cantor has created for us" becomes our motto.

00:13:55.090 --> 00:14:02.470
Furthermore, we must convince our colleagues&nbsp;
that opportunities for research are rife. In&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:02.470 --> 00:14:06.880
mathematics, the kind of free thinking&nbsp;
that allows the pleasant contemplation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:06.880 --> 00:14:12.790
of real numbers—I like to think of them&nbsp;
as basking in the sun—also revels in more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:12.790 --> 00:14:18.910
complicated abstractions. Unlike earlier, more&nbsp;
squeamish generations, we are quite comfortable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:18.910 --> 00:14:25.720
with arbitrary functions from ℝ to ℝ—not just&nbsp;
those given by formulas or computer programs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:25.720 --> 00:14:32.290
but all the others too. With arbitrary&nbsp;
operators on spaces of such functions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:32.290 --> 00:14:39.370
with arbitrary functionals on algebras of such&nbsp;
operators, and so on. Non-measurable functions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:39.370 --> 00:14:47.110
Banach-Tarski paradoxes, various versions of&nbsp;
the axiom of choice, inaccessible cardinals—none&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:47.110 --> 00:14:50.530
of these ruffles our calm in the brave&nbsp;
new world of 20th-century mathematics.

00:14:50.530 --> 00:14:58.390
More than just jobs are opened up here, though.&nbsp;
Our easy attitude to sets can be extended to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:58.390 --> 00:15:03.730
other mathematical objects too. This liberal&nbsp;
approach is captured by what we might call&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:03.730 --> 00:15:13.090
the Axiom of Freedom: An object is constructed&nbsp;
or specified—same thing—by simply stating it.

00:15:13.090 --> 00:15:18.610
To give it one of a multitude of possible&nbsp;
uses of this principle: Suppose you finally&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:18.610 --> 00:15:25.690
constructed a quasi-barreled inverted amorphous&nbsp;
fiber scheme S, and that all that remains is to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:25.690 --> 00:15:32.230
exhibit the space P of all coherent quadratic&nbsp;
forms from S to its dual. In years gone by,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:32.230 --> 00:15:38.560
this would have required fretting about precise&nbsp;
definitions and concrete realizations. These days,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:38.560 --> 00:15:44.590
you need only say, "Let P be the space of&nbsp;
all coherent quadratic functions from S&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:44.590 --> 00:15:48.430
to its dual." Voila, the construction is complete.

00:15:48.430 --> 00:15:55.420
Setbacks and Recovery
At the turn of the century,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:55.420 --> 00:16:00.850
with mathematicians divided in controversy over&nbsp;
the validity and meaning of Cantor's new theory&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:00.850 --> 00:16:06.160
and the role of real numbers, disaster&nbsp;
struck. In one of the most embarrassing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:06.160 --> 00:16:11.380
intellectual deflations of all time, the entire&nbsp;
new theory came crashing down with the discovery&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:11.380 --> 00:16:17.440
of fundamental new paradoxes. These weren't just&nbsp;
the niggling kind of inconsistencies acknowledged&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:24.310
from the start even by Cantor—they were the&nbsp;
full-blown π = √2 type of contradictions that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:24.310 --> 00:16:32.380
ruin one's entire week. A dark time indeed,&nbsp;
but ultimately only a minor setback. After&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:32.380 --> 00:16:37.450
some hesitant and unconvincing attempts to&nbsp;
shore up the subject, we now see that worrying&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:37.450 --> 00:16:44.080
about such issues is largely a waste of time.&nbsp;
Foundations are not really all that necessary.

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:52.270
If pressed by philosophical types, we have a&nbsp;
fallback position: mathematics is based on axioms,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:52.270 --> 00:16:59.050
and the axioms for set theory were spelled out&nbsp;
by Zermelo and Fraenkel. This is the foremost&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:59.050 --> 00:17:06.400
position, also pushed by Hilbert, which got rather&nbsp;
badly bruised by Gödel's results in the 1930s. As&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:06.400 --> 00:17:11.410
a result, most of us closeted Platonists aren't&nbsp;
so keen on this official explanation. But who&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:11.410 --> 00:17:16.960
really wants to get embroiled in philosophical&nbsp;
hair-splittings? An intellectual discipline&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:16.960 --> 00:17:23.380
reflects the spirit and the values of the times,&nbsp;
and these are times of pragmatism and expediency.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:23.380 --> 00:17:30.370
If pressed by our own kind—by mathematicians who&nbsp;
try to point out the imprecision of our cherished&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:30.370 --> 00:17:36.130
fundamental concepts—we respond politely,&nbsp;
we allow them their say, listen patiently,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:36.130 --> 00:17:40.870
and point out that they're basically only&nbsp;
repeating Brouwer's critique of 1918.

00:17:41.700 --> 00:17:47.550
And what about those who obstinately&nbsp;
refuse to understand, who keep on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:47.550 --> 00:17:55.410
insisting that you explain what exactly is a&nbsp;
real fish? Sigh. These people are quibblers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:55.410 --> 00:18:02.280
philosophical quibblers at that, and they are&nbsp;
best ignored. After all, you've got a job to do.

00:18:04.920 --> 00:18:09.330
Looking to the Future
As pragmatism and expediency&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:09.330 --> 00:18:14.040
don't look to be departing the modern world&nbsp;
anytime soon, I'm confident that the lessons&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:14.040 --> 00:18:18.840
mathematicians have learned can be fruitfully&nbsp;
applied to biology. Don't expect to convince&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:18.840 --> 00:18:23.610
your contemporaries about the importance&nbsp;
of real fish. Recruit a few top names,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:23.610 --> 00:18:29.340
work on the future generations, keep&nbsp;
the employment prospects firmly in view,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:29.340 --> 00:18:33.720
and life theory will take its rightful&nbsp;
place in the scientific world.

00:18:33.720 --> 00:18:41.640
As for me, this little advice-giving has got&nbsp;
me thinking. Mathematicians are themselves a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:41.640 --> 00:18:47.520
bit hard-pressed these days for employment. The&nbsp;
huge amount of time and effort required to rewrite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:47.520 --> 00:18:53.280
modern mathematics using only computable numbers,&nbsp;
computable functions, computable everything would&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:53.280 --> 00:19:01.560
keep us busy for decades. Unpleasant, a lot of&nbsp;
hard work that would be, but hard work means jobs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:01.560 --> 00:19:12.570
grants, and pensions. Maybe Aristotle, Archimedes,&nbsp;
Newton, Euler, Gauss, Kronecker, Borel, Lebesgue,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:12.570 --> 00:19:19.380
Poincaré, Weyl, Brouwer, and the others were&nbsp;
right—there is something fishy about real numbers.

00:19:23.880 --> 00:19:28.530
Alright, so that's my little article&nbsp;
called Real Fish, Real Numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:28.530 --> 00:19:34.350
Real Jobs, which I published in 1999 in&nbsp;
The Mathematical Intelligencer. So you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:34.350 --> 00:19:40.320
might want to know what kind of response&nbsp;
I've gotten. How many dozen citations has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:40.320 --> 00:19:46.500
this lovely and illuminating paper received?&nbsp;
It's received, as far as I know, one citation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:46.500 --> 00:19:55.200
and I have gotten correspondence from, I think,&nbsp;
one or two people concerning it. I once had&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:55.200 --> 00:19:59.730
a roommate at a conference in New Zealand from&nbsp;
Belgium, and we were talking about real numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:59.730 --> 00:20:06.330
and it turned out that he had read an article some&nbsp;
time back about somebody who was also adopting a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:06.330 --> 00:20:09.810
heretical position. It turned out to&nbsp;
be my article, so I was a little bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:09.810 --> 00:20:15.510
amused by that—that at least people have read the&nbsp;
article and maybe not responded directly to it.

00:20:15.510 --> 00:20:25.260
But the point is that a single voice is easily&nbsp;
ignored. People have a lot of incentive to keep&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:25.260 --> 00:20:31.560
on thinking the same way, to keep on going&nbsp;
in the same direction that they used to,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:31.560 --> 00:20:36.660
which is comfortable and pleasant, and&nbsp;
they, of course, are buttressed by the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:36.660 --> 00:20:45.990
support of a lot of like-thinking colleagues.&nbsp;
It's not so easy to change the direction of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:45.990 --> 00:20:52.500
mathematics. And what I'm going to talk about&nbsp;
in my next video is I'm going to address this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:52.500 --> 00:20:57.600
issue of what mathematics would actually&nbsp;
look like if we did seriously contemplate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:57.600 --> 00:21:04.140
getting rid of real numbers. What would&nbsp;
happen? Would it all just collapse? What&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:04.140 --> 00:21:10.140
would mathematics look like without real&nbsp;
numbers? I hope you'll join me for that.

00:21:10.140 --> 00:21:14.100
I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

